fields.review_content: Claude Monet, French impressionist painter, painted a large series of paintings of this cathedral. It is a great site for photography.

The Forbidden City is one of great tourist destinations of Beijing, and for that reason, it is always packed with visitors. There are vendors outside trying to make money off of these travelers, selling fake watches and other cheap goods. Still though, the destination is incredibly beautiful decorated in beautiful reds and golds. The site is beautiful, and the history makes the site even more interesting.

Santorini is one of the most beautiful places I've ever been. The island is entirely picturesque from the little white and blue houses to the beautiful blue water. At times, the fish and donkey smell makes the air unpleasant, but the views are utterly spectacular.

In terms of architectural advances and history, the Parthenon cannot be beat in its significance. This destination is much better seen from the streets of Athens than from the crowded up close perspective. Late at night, teh streets of Athens fill up as people get ready to eat dinner. Small cafes bustle with excitement as souvlaki and gyros with amazing french fries are served to the evening visitors.

Visiting the Ruins of Ephesus is remarkably enriching. The site is incredibly beautiful and ancient and is not laced with the usual tourists that occupy so many previous Wonders of the World. Cheap knock-off goods and delicious Turkish Delight can also be bought at nearby marketplaces. "Genuine Fake Watches" were being sold when I was there.

Whistler Blackcomb is one of the most majestic ski resorts out there. The mountain gets remarkable amounts of snow (at least at the top) and has a whole mile of vertical drop. The apres-ski at Whistler is also competitive with the famous apres-ski life of Vail. There are many restaurants to pick from and much entertainment. I would personally recommend Mongolie Grill and then Cows for delicious ice cream. The mountain has two flaws: its crowds and its 'tropical' weather at the base and on the lower parts of the mountain.

Big Sky is truly a hidden gem. There are no crowds and crazy large amounts of snow. It is perfect for hard core skiiers looking for powder runs and empty slopes. There is not much in the middle of montana, but the views alone will leave you breathless.
The story of the Terracota Warriors is breathtaking, and they are simply remarkable to look at. Each one is beautifully unique, and they are just something worth seeing in a lifetime.

Stadiwm y Mileniwm, which means Millennium Stadium in Welsh, is a multifunctional stadium. Frankly, it is not very remarkable as a sports stadium because it is mainly used by Welsh leagues. I visited this stadium because its underground area appeared in Doctor Who, but the underground region is not open to public.

Musee d'Orsay is famous for its collection of impressionist and post-impressionist art works.
Monet, Renoir, Manet and Degas are all French; Van Gogh is Dutch, yet he was most productive when he was France. So France is clearly the centre of impressionism. If you love impressionism, Muess d'Orsay is decidedly the best museum to visit.  

official website: http://www.musee-orsay.fr/en/home.html

All tourist visit Eiffel Tower even though they know it is not an interesting attraction. However, visiting Eiffel does not mean climbing Eiffel; I do not understand why so many tourists insist on climbing to the top of Eiffel. 
If you go to Paris in Tourist Season which sadly is when you have time to travel, I do not recommend climbing stairs or taking lift to the top. Paris is a beautiful city, but aerial view is not the best view to see it.

Everybody can find something interesting in the Louvre because of its extensive collection. Personally, I  visit the Louvre every time I go to Paris, so I strongly recommend visiting this museum. 
It is impossible to visit every section, so plan your tour in advance according to interests. Besides, the ticket is only 10. 
For the interests of hass students: There is an academy affiliated to the Louvre called Ecole du Louvre, which offers courses in art history, archaeology etc.

Place de la Concorde is best known for the Luxor Obelisk which French stole from Egypt. Historically, the square is also related to French Revolution. It locates at the end of Champs-Élysées, so it is also a convenient location to watch Tour de France or to watch crazy French during Tour de France.
There are lots of luxury shops, pigeons, crepes and tourists.

You will understand better why French people started revolution if you visit Versailles. Visiting all palaces and gardens can take a day, but Versailles is worth the time. 
One concern may be transportation: We drove to Versailles, which took 1-2 hours.  However, it is very convenient to take a train (RER) from Paris to Versailles because Versailles is actually in the suburb of Paris. Inside Versailles, you can walk/ bike/ take shuttle, though I personally think walking is a bit challenging.

Ginza is supposed to be the most expensive area for shopping and food in Tokyo. I thought it is a Japanese version of Champs Elysees with narrower street and fewer trees.
However, I went to Ginza for Melon-pan! If you watch Shakugan no Shana, you should know how important Melon-pan is. Unfortunately, Misaki is not a real city, so the best place for Melon-pan is Ginza because it is the cradle of Melon-pan.

CERN is the European Organization for Nuclear Research. I think all experimental physicists work at CERN at some point of their life. Anyone can visit CERN as a tourist even if he does not work there; I am not sure if appointment is needed.
